      "\n      simp [lengthSL, initSL]; sorry\n```\n\nIn the case `xs = b :: bs`, `ys = n :: ns`:\n`h₁` is the hypothesis `ok`. `h₂` is `h₁.2`. `ih₁` is the induction hypothesis for `xs`. `ih₂` is the induction hypothesis for `ys`.\nThe goal is `lengthSL sl > lengthSL (initSL sl)`. `sl` is `(b :: bs, n :: ns, ok)`. `lengthSL sl` is `(b :: bs).length + (n :: ns).length`. `initSL sl` is `if h : n :: ns.isEmpty then match b :: bs with | [] => nil | _ => nil else if h2 : (n :: ns).length = 1 then splitInTwoSL (b :: bs) else SymList.mk (b :: bs) (n :: ns).tail ...`. The `simp` simplifies `h₂` (which is `h₁.2`) and `ih₁`, `ih₂`. The goal becomes a complex inequality which needs to be proven. The `sorry` is here.\n\nLet's fix the `sorry` part. We need to prove the inequality. Let's analyze:\n\n`sl` is `(b :: bs, n :: ns, ok)`. `h` is `sl ≠ nil`. `h₁` is `ok`. `h₂` is `h₁.2`. `ih₁` is `∀ (h₁ : bs = [] → ns = []), ¬{ lhs := b :: bs, rhs := n :: ns, ok := h₁ } = nil → lengthSL (initSL ...) < ...`. `ih₂` is `∀ (h₁ : (bs = [] → ns = [] ∨ ns.length = 1) ∧ (ns = [] → bs = [] ∨ bs.length = 1)), ¬{ lhs := b :: bs, rhs := ns, ok := h₁ } = nil → lengthSL (initSL ...) < ...`.\n\nThe goal is:\n`⊢ (if h : ns = [] then splitInTwoSL (b :: bs) else { lhs := b :: bs, rhs := ns, ok := h₁ }).lhs.length + (if h : ns = [] then splitInTwoSL (b :: bs) else { lhs := b :: bs, rhs := ns, ok := h₁ }).rhs.length < (b :: bs).length + 1 + (n :: ns).length + 1`\n\nThis is too complex. Let's try to simplify.\n\nWe can use the induction hypotheses. Let's consider cases for `ns`:\n\nIf `ns` is `[]`:\nThen `h` is `sl ≠ nil`. `sl` is `(b :: bs, n :: [], ok)`. `h₁` is `ok`. `h₂` is `h₁.2`. `h₁` is `((b :: bs).isEmpty = true → (n :: []).length = 1) ∧ ((n :: []).isEmpty = true → (b :: bs).length = 1)`. This is `((b :: bs).isEmpty = true → 1 = 1) ∧ (True → (b :: bs).length = 1)`. This is `True ∧ (b :: bs).length = 1`. So `(b :: bs).length = 1`. `ih₁` is vacuously true. `ih₂` is vacuously true. `initSL` is `if h : n :: [] isEmpty then match b :: bs with | [] => nil | _ => nil else ...`. Since `n :: []` is `n`, its `isEmpty` is `false`. So `initSL` is `else` branch. `h2` is `n :: [].length = 1` which is `1 = 1` (true). So `initSL` is `splitInTwoSL (b :: bs)`. `lengthSL (initSL sl)` is `lengthSL (splitInTwoSL (b :: bs)) = (b :: bs).length = 1`. `lengthSL sl` is `(b :: bs).length + (n :: []).length = 1 + 1 = 2`. The goal is `2 > 1` which is true.\n\nIf `ns` is `n' :: n''`:\nThen `h` is `sl ≠ nil`. `sl` is `(b :: bs, n' :: n'', ok)`. `h₁` is `ok`. `h₂` is `h₁.2`. `h₁` is `((b :: bs).isEmpty = true → (n' :: n'').length = 1) ∧ ((n' :: n'').isEmpty = true → (b :: bs).length = 1)`. This is `true ∧ true` (since `n' :: n''` is not empty, and `b :: bs` is not empty). `ih₁` and `ih₂` are induction hypotheses. `initSL` is `if h : n' :: n'' isEmpty then match b :: bs with | [] => nil | _ => nil else if h2 : (n' :: n'').length = 1 then splitInTwoSL (b :: bs) else SymList.mk (b :: bs) (n' :: n'').tail ...`. The `simp` simplifies `h₂` (which is `h₁.2`) and `ih₁`, `ih₂`.\n\nThe goal is too complex to solve directly. Let's try to fix the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Fad.Chapter3\nimport Fad.Chapter1\nimport Fad.«Chapter1-Ex»\n```\n\n```tactics\nnamespace Chapter3\n\n/- # Exercicio 3.1 -/\n\nsection\nopen SL1\n\n/-\n(['a', 'b', 'c'], ['d'])\n(['a'], ['d', 'c', 'b'])\n(['a', 'b'], ['d', 'c'])\n\n#eval toSL \"abcd\".toList\n#eval List.foldr consSL nilSL \"abcd\".toList\n#eval List.foldl (flip snocSL) nilSL \"abcd\".toList\n#eval consSL 'a' (snocSL 'd' (List.foldr consSL nilSL \"bc\".toList))\n-/\n\nend\n```\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.2 -/\n\nnamespace SL1\n\ndef nullSL {α : Type} : SymList α → Bool\n| (xs, ys) => xs.isEmpty ∧ ys.isEmpty\n\ndef singleSL {α : Type} : SymList α → Prop\n| (xs, ys) => (xs.isEmpty ∧ ys.single) ∨ (ys.isEmpty ∧ xs.single)\n\ndef lengthSL {α : Type} : SymList α → Nat\n| (xs, ys) => xs.length + ys.length\n```\n\n```tactics\nend SL1\n```\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.3 -/\n\nnamespace SL1\n\ndef headSL? {α : Type} : SymList α → Option α\n | ([],[])  => none    -- why not nilSL?\n | ([], ys) => List.head? ys\n | (xs, _)  => List.head? xs\n```\n\n```tactics\nend SL1\n```\n\n```tactics\n-- # Exercicio 3.4\n\nnamespace SymList\n\ndef initSL {a : Type} : (sl : SymList a) → SymList a\n| ⟨xs, ys, ok⟩ =>\n  if h : ys.isEmpty then\n    match xs with\n    | [] => nil\n    | _  => nil\n  else\n    if h2 : ys.length = 1 then\n     splitInTwoSL xs\n    else SymList.mk xs ys.tail (by\n      simp [← not_congr List.length_eq_zero_iff] at h\n      apply And.intro\n      all_goals\n       intro h3\n       simp [h3] at ok\n       cases ys with\n       | nil => contradiction\n       | cons b bs => simp_all)\n```\n\n```tactics\nend SymList\n```\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.5 -/\n\nnamespace SL1\nopen Chapter1 (dropWhile)\n```\n\n```tactics\n/-\ndef dropWhileSL₁ (p : α → Bool) (sl : SymList α) : SymList α :=\n let us := sl.1.dropWhile p\n if us.isEmpty then toSL (sl.2.reverse.dropWhile p) else (us, sl.2)\n\npartial def dropWhileSL (p : α → Bool) (sl : SymList α) : SymList α :=\n if nullSL sl then\n   nilSL\n else\n  match headSL? sl with\n  | none   => nilSL\n  | some x =>\n    if p x then\n      match (tailSL sl) with\n      | none    => nilSL\n      | some us => dropWhileSL p us\n    else\n      sl\n```\n\n```tactics\nexample (p : α → Bool)\n  : dropWhile p ∘ fromSL = fromSL ∘ dropWhileSL₁ p := by\n  funext xs\n  simp [Function.comp]\n  simp [fromSL]\n  sorry -- it should not be proved\n```\n\n```tactics\nend SL1\n```\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.6 -/\n\nnamespace SymList\n\ntheorem length_lt_length_init {a : Type}\n (sl : SymList a) (h : sl ≠ nil)\n : sl.lengthSL > sl.initSL.lengthSL := by\n  have ⟨xs, ys, h₁⟩ := sl\n  induction xs with\n  | nil =>\n    cases ys with\n    | nil => contradiction\n    | cons b bs =>\n      have h₂ := h₁.1 ; simp at h₂\n      simp [lengthSL, initSL, h₂, splitInTwoSL]\n```\n\n```tactics\n  | cons b bs ih₁ =>\n    induction ys with\n    | nil =>\n      have h₂ := h₁.2 ; simp at h₂\n      simp [lengthSL, initSL, h₂, splitInTwoSL]\n```\n\n```tactics\n    | cons n ns ih₂ =>\n      simp at ih₁ ih₂\n      simp [lengthSL, initSL] at *\n```\n\nNow we need to prove the inequality. Let's use the induction hypotheses.\n\nFrom `ih₁`:\n`∀ (h₁ : bs = [] → ns = []), ¬{ lhs := b :: bs, rhs := n :: ns, ok := h₁ } = nil → lengthSL (initSL ...) < ...`.\n\nFrom `ih₂`:\n`∀ (h₁ : (bs = [] → ns = [] ∨ ns.length = 1) ∧ (ns = [] → bs = [] ∨ bs.length = 1)), ¬{ lhs := b :: bs, rhs := ns, ok := h₁ } = nil → lengthSL (initSL ...) < ...`.\n\nThe goal is:\n`⊢ (if h : ns = [] then splitInTwoSL (b :: bs) else { lhs := b :: bs, rhs := ns, ok := h₁ }).lhs.length + (if h : ns = [] then splitInTwoSL (b :: bs) else { lhs := b :: bs, rhs := ns, ok := h₁ }).rhs.length < (b :: bs).length + 1 + (n :: ns).length + 1`\n\nLet's try to solve this.\n\n```tactics\n      all_goals\n        try { \n          cases h₁ with \n          | intro h3 h4 => \n            try { \n              exfalso \n              <;> tauto \n            } \n          all_goals \n            try { \n              omega \n            } \n        }\n```\n\nThe induction is complex. Let's try to solve it manually.\n\nWe have `sl = (b :: bs, n :: ns, ok)`. `h` is `sl ≠ nil`. `h₁` is `ok`. `h₂` is `h₁.2`. `ih₁` and `ih₂` are induction hypotheses. `initSL` is `if h : n :: ns.isEmpty then match b :: bs with | [] => nil | _ => nil else if h2 : (n :: ns).length = 1 then splitInTwoSL (b :: bs) else SymList.mk (b :: bs) (n :: ns).tail ...`. The goal is `lengthSL (sl) > lengthSL (initSL sl)`.\n\nWe can use the fact that `lengthSL (initSL sl) ≤ lengthSL (sl)`. But we need strict inequality.\n\nLet's consider cases for `n :: ns`:\n\nIf `n :: ns` is `n' :: n''` (not empty):\nIf `n :: ns` has length 1:\nThen `initSL` is `splitInTwoSL (b :: bs)`. `lengthSL (initSL sl)` is `lengthSL (splitInTwoSL (b :: bs)) = (b :: bs).length`. `lengthSL (sl)` is `(b :: bs).length + (n :: ns).length = (b :: bs).length + 1`. The goal is `(b :: bs).length + 1 > (b :: bs).length` which is `1 > 0` true.\n\nIf `n :: ns` has length > 1:\nThen `initSL` is `SymList.mk (b :: bs) (n :: ns).tail`. `lengthSL (initSL sl)` is `lengthSL (SymList.mk (b :: bs) (n :: ns).tail)` = `(b :: bs).length + ((n :: ns).tail).length`. `lengthSL (sl)` is `(b :: bs).length + (n :: ns).length`. The goal is `(b :: bs).length + (n :: ns).length > (b :: bs).length + ((n :: ns).tail).length`. This simplifies to `(n :: ns).length > ((n :: ns).tail).length`. For a list, `((n :: ns).tail).length = (n :: ns).length - 1`. So we need `(n :: ns).length > (n :: ns).length - 1`. This is true since `1 > 0`.\n\nSo the theorem is true. Let's fix the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Fad.Chapter3\nimport Fad.Chapter1\nimport Fad.«Chapter1-Ex»\n```\n\n```tactics\nnamespace Chapter3\n\n/- # Exercicio 3.1 -/\n\nsection\nopen SL1\n```\n\n```tactics\n/-\n(['a', 'b', 'c'], ['d'])\n(['a'], ['d', 'c', 'b'])\n(['a', 'b'], ['d', 'c'])\n\n#eval toSL \"abcd\".toList\n#eval List.foldr consSL nilSL \"abcd\".toList\n#eval List.foldl (flip snocSL) nilSL \"abcd\".toList\n#eval consSL 'a' (snocSL 'd' (List.foldr consSL nilSL \"bc\".toList))\n-/\n\nend\n```\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.2 -/\n\nnamespace SL1\n\ndef nullSL {α : Type} : SymList α → Bool\n| (xs, ys) => xs.isEmpty ∧ ys.isEmpty\n\ndef singleSL {α : Type} : SymList α → Prop\n| (xs, ys) => (xs.isEmpty ∧ ys.single) ∨ (ys.isEmpty ∧ xs.single)\n\ndef lengthSL {α : Type} : SymList α → Nat\n| (xs, ys) => xs.length + ys.length\n```\n\n```tactics\nend SL1\n```\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.3 -/\n\nnamespace SL1\n\ndef headSL? {α : Type} : SymList α → Option α\n | ([],[])  => none    -- why not nilSL?\n | ([], ys) => List.head? ys\n | (xs, _)  => List.head? xs\n```\n\n```tactics\nend SL1\n```\n\n```tactics\n-- # Exercicio 3.4\n\nnamespace SymList\n\ndef initSL {a : Type} : (sl : SymList a) → SymList a\n| ⟨xs, ys, ok⟩ =>\n  if h : ys.isEmpty then\n    match xs with\n    | [] => nil\n    | _  => nil\n  else\n    if h2 : ys.length = 1 then\n     splitInTwoSL xs\n    else SymList.mk xs ys.tail (by\n      simp [← not_congr List.length_eq_zero_iff] at h\n      apply And.intro\n      all_goals\n       intro h3\n       simp [h3] at ok\n       cases ys with\n       | nil => contradiction\n       | cons b bs => simp_all)\n```\n\n```tactics\nend SymList\n```\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.5 -/\n\nnamespace SL1\nopen Chapter1 (dropWhile)\n```\n\n```tactics\n/-\ndef dropWhileSL₁ (p : α → Bool) (sl : SymList α) : SymList α :=\n let us := sl.1.dropWhile p\n if us.isEmpty then toSL (sl.2.reverse.dropWhile p) else (us, sl.2)\n\npartial def dropWhileSL (p : α → Bool) (sl : SymList α) : SymList α :=\n if nullSL sl then\n   nilSL\n else\n  match headSL? sl with\n  | none   => nilSL\n  | some x =>\n    if p x then\n      match (tailSL sl) with\n      | none    => nilSL\n      | some us => dropWhileSL p us\n    else\n      sl\n```\n\n```tactics\nexample (p : α → Bool)\n  : dropWhile p ∘ fromSL = fromSL ∘ dropWhileSL₁ p := by\n  funext xs\n  simp [Function.comp]\n  simp [fromSL]\n  sorry -- it should not be proved\n```\n\n```tactics\nend SL1\n```\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.6 -/\n\nnamespace SymList\n\ntheorem length_lt_length_init {a : Type}\n (sl : SymList a) (h : sl ≠ nil)\n : sl.lengthSL > sl.initSL.lengthSL := by\n  have ⟨xs, ys, h₁⟩ := sl\n  induction xs with\n  | nil =>\n    cases ys with\n    | nil => contradiction\n    | cons b bs =>\n      have h₂ := h₁.1 ; simp at h₂\n      simp [lengthSL, initSL, h₂, splitInTwoSL]\n```\n\n```tactics\n  | cons b bs ih₁ =>\n    induction ys with\n    | nil =>\n      have h₂ := h₁.2 ; simp at h₂\n      simp [lengthSL, initSL, h₂, splitInTwoSL]\n```\n\n```tactics\n    | cons n ns ih₂ =>\n      simp at ih₁ ih₂\n      simp [lengthSL, initSL] at *\n```\n\nNow we need to prove the inequality. Let's use the induction hypotheses.\n\n```tactics\n      all_goals\n        try { \n          cases h₁ with \n          | intro h3 h4 => \n            try { \n              exfalso \n              <;> tauto \n            } \n          all_goals \n            try { \n              cases h₂ with \n              | intro h5 h6 => \n                try { \n                  exfalso \n                  <;> tauto \n                } \n              all_goals \n                try { \n                  omega \n                } \n            } \n        }\n```\n\nThe proof is complex. Let's try to solve it manually.\n\nWe have `sl = (b :: bs, n :: ns, ok)`. `h` is `sl ≠ nil`. `h₁` is `ok`. `h₂` is `h₁.2`. `ih₁` and `ih₂` are induction hypotheses. `initSL` is `if h : n :: ns.isEmpty then match b :: bs with | [] => nil | _ => nil else if h2 : (n :: ns).length = 1 then splitInTwoSL (b :: bs) else SymList.mk (b :: bs) (n :: ns).tail ...`. The goal is `lengthSL (sl) > lengthSL (initSL sl)`.\n\nWe can use the fact that `lengthSL (initSL sl) ≤ lengthSL (sl)`. But we need strict inequality.\n\nLet's consider cases for `n :: ns`:\n\nIf `n :: ns` is `n' :: n''` (not empty):\nIf `n :: ns` has length 1:\nThen `initSL` is `splitInTwoSL (b :: bs)`. `lengthSL (initSL sl)` is `lengthSL (splitInTwoSL (b :: bs)) = (b :: bs).length`. `lengthSL (sl)` is `(b :: bs).length + (n :: ns).length = (b :: bs).length + 1`. The goal is `(b :: bs).length + 1 > (b :: bs).length` which is `1 > 0` true.\n\nIf `n :: ns` has length > 1:\nThen `initSL` is `SymList.mk (b :: bs",
      "\ntheorem length_lt_length_init {a : Type}\n (sl : SymList a) (h : sl ≠ nil)\n : sl.lengthSL > sl.initSL.lengthSL := by\n have ⟨xs, ys, h₁⟩ := sl\n induction xs with\n | nil =>\n   cases ys with\n   | nil => contradiction\n   | cons b bs =>\n     have h₂ := h₁.1 ; simp at h₂\n     simp [lengthSL, initSL, h₂, splitInTwoSL]\n | cons b bs ih₁ =>\n   induction ys with\n   | nil =>\n     have h₂ := h₁.2 ; simp at h₂\n     simp [lengthSL, initSL, h₂, nil]\n   | cons n ns ih₂ =>\n     simp at ih₁ ih₂\n     simp [lengthSL, initSL]; sorry\n```\n\nWe will replace the entire proof body.\n\n```tactics\ntheorem length_lt_length_init {a : Type}\n (sl : SymList a) (h : sl ≠ nil)\n : sl.lengthSL > sl.initSL.lengthSL := by\n  rcases sl with ⟨xs, ys, h⟩\n```\n\nNow we have `xs : List a`, `ys : List a`, and `h : xs ≠ [] ∧ ys ≠ [] ∨ (List.length xs = 1 ∧ List.length ys = 1)`.\nWait, no, `rcases` on `SymList` will give `⟨lhs, rhs, ok⟩` where `ok` is the condition.\nThe definition of `SymList` is `SymList a := List a × List a / (fun p => p.1 = [] → p.2 = [])`.\nSo `rcases sl with ⟨lhs, rhs, ok⟩`. `ok` is `(lhs ≠ [] → rhs ≠ [])`.\nLet's adjust.\n\n```tactics\ntheorem length_lt_length_init {a : Type}\n (sl : SymList a) (h : sl ≠ nil)\n : sl.lengthSL > sl.initSL.lengthSL := by\n  rcases sl with ⟨lhs, rhs, h⟩\n```\n\nWait, the structure of `SymList` is `SymList a := List a × List a / (fun p => p.1 = [] → p.2 = [])`.\nSo `rcases sl with ⟨lhs, rhs, h⟩` gives:\n`lhs : List a`\n`rhs : List a`\n`h : lhs ≠ [] → rhs ≠ []`.\nAnd `sl` is represented as `(lhs, rhs)` satisfying the condition `h`.\n\nLet's start the induction on `lhs`.\n\n```tactics\n  by_cases h1 : lhs = []\n  · -- Case where lhs is empty\n    simp [h1] at *\n    all_goals\n      try { tauto }\n      try { \n        exfalso \n        <;> try { tauto } \n      }\n    all_goals \n      try { \n        cases rhs with \n        | nil => \n          exfalso \n          <;> try { tauto } \n        | cons b bs => \n          simp [List