    - Since `List.dropLast xs` is not empty, `xs` must have at least one element. So `xs.length ≥ 1`.
    - Then `List.dropLast xs` has length `xs.length - 1`.
- `sl.initSL.lengthSL = (List.dropLast xs).length + (List.reverse (List.dropLast ys)).length = (xs.length - 1) + 0 = xs.length - 1`.
- `sl.lengthSL - sl.initSL.lengthSL = (xs.length + 1) - (xs.length - 1) = 2 > 0`. This is valid.

Case 3: `sl = ⟨xs, ys, ok⟩` where `ys` has length > 1.
- `sl = ⟨xs, ys, ok⟩`.
- `sl.initSL = ⟨xs, List.dropLast ys, ok'⟩`.
  - `ok'` implies `xs` is not empty or `List.dropLast ys` is not empty or `List.dropLast ys` has length 1.
  - Since `List.dropLast ys` has length `ys.length - 1`. If `ys.length > 1`, then `List.dropLast ys` has length ≥ 1. So `List.dropLast ys` is not empty.
  - Thus `ok'` is satisfied.
- `sl.lengthSL = xs.length + ys.length`.
- `sl.initSL.lengthSL = xs.length + (List.dropLast ys).length = xs.length + (ys.length - 1)`.
- `sl.lengthSL - sl.initSL.lengthSL = (xs.length + ys.length) - (xs.length + ys.length - 1) = 1 > 0`. This is valid.

So in all valid cases (where `sl ≠ nil`), `sl.lengthSL > sl.initSL.lengthSL`.

